	<h3>Input and Events</h3>
	
	<p>The examples so far have involved one type of request: the <em>page render request</em>. To recap:</p>
	
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Page render requests</strong> target a specific page. Tapestry activates the page, 
		renders it to HTML, and returns it to the client.</li>
	</ul>

	<p>To send input and events to the server, there is a second type of request: the <em>component event request</em>.</p>
	
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Component event requests</strong> target a specific component on the page. Tapestry activates 
		the page, triggers an event on the component, and the component may bubble up events for the containing page 
		or components to react to.</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>This is really significant:</strong> the container, ie. the page or component; that chose to render 
	a particular component, is then able to react to input and events sent to that component. This is perfect! 
	What could be better placed to understand the meaning of the input or event than the container that chose to 
	render that component.</p>

    <p>The 2 most used components for generating <em>component event requests</em> are these:</p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Form</strong>.  When submitted, the request carries your input to the corresponding Form on the server.</li>
        <li><strong>EventLink</strong>.  When clicked, the request carries an event name and parameters to the corresponding 
        	EventLink on the server.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Others include <strong>ActionLink</strong> and <strong>GridPager</strong>.</p>
    
    <p>In later examples, when we use <strong>Ajax</strong>, we will find that <strong><em>every</em> component 
    can send a component event request!</strong></p>

